WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.080
Good morning, everyone, and welcome to this session on building effective data science

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:12.080
teams.

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:15.200
I'm so happy to see you all here.

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:17.320
We'll have a host of fantastic speakers.

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:19.440
Each one will have 20 minutes today.

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:22.480
That includes questions, if time permits.

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:28.440
And it is my great pleasure to welcome the first speaker, Daniel Woody, up to the stage.

00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:29.440
Please come in.

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:30.440
All right.

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:31.440
Thanks, everyone.

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:41.799
I have to start this off with a little story.

00:00:41.799 --> 00:00:47.840
So actually last week I was having a meeting with my manager, and we were doing like a

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:51.360
performance review check-in.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:55.980
And he had lots of positive feedback about, you know, how I'm building this prototyping

00:00:55.980 --> 00:01:01.540
competency within Lilly, and, you know, I've done a great job with coming up with like

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:08.059
an operating model and having metrics for the team and setting the direction.

00:01:08.059 --> 00:01:11.940
But he gave me some feedback, too, on things to improve on.

00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:16.900
And the thing to improve on is my presentation skills.

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:23.860
And so this is a great opportunity to, you know, put some of that to work.

00:01:23.860 --> 00:01:25.300
So that was Tuesday of last week.

00:01:25.300 --> 00:01:32.540
And then Wednesday of last week, I get on LinkedIn, get on the internet, and I see this.

00:01:32.540 --> 00:01:36.980
You know, must-haves for this conference is my talk.

00:01:36.980 --> 00:01:42.099
And then this company put out a top ten and put my talk as number one.

00:01:42.099 --> 00:01:48.419
And I was like, we need to level set a little bit here, guys.

00:01:48.419 --> 00:01:49.739
So yeah.

00:01:49.739 --> 00:01:53.379
Just putting that out there.

00:01:53.379 --> 00:01:56.699
So thanks, everyone, for coming to the talk today.

00:01:56.699 --> 00:01:58.220
Here's the rough agenda.

00:01:58.220 --> 00:02:02.879
So I'll be going over, you know, why to build a prototyping capability.

00:02:02.879 --> 00:02:08.619
Something I've put together, I'm calling this statistical sciences hierarchy of needs based

00:02:08.619 --> 00:02:11.220
on Maslow's hierarchy of needs.

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:15.660
I'm going to walk through our process a little bit.

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:17.779
How we define a prototype.

00:02:17.779 --> 00:02:19.699
How we operate as a team.

00:02:19.699 --> 00:02:21.979
And lessons learned.

00:02:21.979 --> 00:02:27.500
And one thing I'll point out is when I say, like, we as a team, it's me and one other

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:28.500
guy.

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:32.300
We're a very scrappy operation.

00:02:32.300 --> 00:02:34.179
So yeah.

00:02:34.179 --> 00:02:35.179
Which I like.

00:02:35.179 --> 00:02:41.259
We're able to deliver real fast.

00:02:41.259 --> 00:02:42.259
So yeah.

00:02:42.259 --> 00:02:47.419
On the topic of why to build a prototyping capability, you know, they're useful and quickly

00:02:47.419 --> 00:02:49.539
vetting new ideas.

00:02:49.539 --> 00:02:53.380
So I work in pharma in the stats department.

00:02:53.380 --> 00:02:57.259
And innovation can be hard in that group.

00:02:57.259 --> 00:03:01.460
And a lot of it is there's just a fear of risk taking.

00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:08.600
And having the prototyping capability allows you to quickly vet, you know, new technologies

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:11.339
that you may want to explore.

00:03:11.339 --> 00:03:17.100
And it really provides an accelerator to the broader strategy for the organization.

00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:18.860
And so, yeah.

00:03:18.860 --> 00:03:25.059
It's incredibly valuable for elevating the conversation.

00:03:25.059 --> 00:03:27.660
Not just with your team, but with leadership.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:31.300
Because a lot of times they like to go big and it slows them down.

00:03:31.300 --> 00:03:36.699
Whereas going small allows them to, you know, test out these new ideas in kind of a risk

00:03:36.699 --> 00:03:39.059
averse way.

00:03:39.059 --> 00:03:41.300
Yeah.

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:45.699
So the statistical science is hierarchy of needs.

00:03:45.699 --> 00:03:52.259
So if you've seen Maslow's hierarchy of needs, it's, you know, based on that, obviously.

00:03:52.259 --> 00:04:01.580
Which is a schema or framework for kind of finding, you know, fulfillment and being healthy.

00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:09.860
And, you know, when applying it to our organization, this is kind of my latest draft with it.

00:04:09.860 --> 00:04:11.500
It's always kind of updating.

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:20.380
But yeah, for us, we have IT infrastructure at the foundation of it.

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:27.980
Which can be kind of foreign, I think, to people that are traditional statisticians.

00:04:27.980 --> 00:04:30.299
But yeah.

00:04:30.299 --> 00:04:34.980
It is kind of the bedrock for everything else that we do.

00:04:35.859 --> 00:04:42.179
And having that value and perspective is kind of critical to progress in the other layers.

00:04:42.179 --> 00:04:48.140
And so, you know, once you have, you know, something in place or strategy in place for

00:04:48.140 --> 00:04:52.619
moving IT infrastructure forward, then you can start to look at, like, your tools and

00:04:52.619 --> 00:04:54.380
your capabilities.

00:04:54.380 --> 00:05:00.739
And so for us, the tools are building R packages, Shiny applications.

00:05:00.739 --> 00:05:06.380
And on the capability side, it's, you know, we work with drug development teams.

00:05:06.380 --> 00:05:08.619
And so we're working on clinical trials.

00:05:08.619 --> 00:05:15.779
And so it's kind of taking those tools and using them for those product teams.

00:05:15.779 --> 00:05:19.459
And then beyond that, we also have training.

00:05:19.459 --> 00:05:24.140
And so once you have kind of your tools narrowed down, then you're looking at, okay, how do

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:26.579
you upskill the organization?

00:05:26.579 --> 00:05:30.540
Which is a big task.

00:05:31.339 --> 00:05:34.019
And then beyond that, we have the prototypes team.

00:05:34.019 --> 00:05:38.820
And so with the prototypes team, like I said, we're an accelerator.

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:41.299
And so we're working in IT infrastructure.

00:05:41.299 --> 00:05:43.579
We're working in the tools and capabilities.

00:05:43.579 --> 00:05:46.859
And we're even testing out new training modalities.

00:05:46.859 --> 00:05:54.420
And our job is really to make those lower levels kind of work in harmony better.

00:05:54.420 --> 00:06:00.739
And then at the top, you have self-actualization or, yeah, just everything working in the direction

00:06:00.739 --> 00:06:01.739
you want it to.

00:06:01.739 --> 00:06:08.359
So that is kind of our north star, if you will.

00:06:08.359 --> 00:06:09.619
So our process.

00:06:09.619 --> 00:06:10.859
Very simple.

00:06:10.859 --> 00:06:19.579
I point this out because a lot of times people can get lost in technology and say, oh, I've

00:06:19.579 --> 00:06:22.579
got, you know, this new hammer.

00:06:22.619 --> 00:06:24.299
And then they just go and find the nails.

00:06:24.299 --> 00:06:28.980
But, you know, that may not be the best way to start out.

00:06:28.980 --> 00:06:35.019
And so, yeah, obviously find the problem.

00:06:35.019 --> 00:06:38.239
Once you have the problem, solve it in some way.

00:06:38.239 --> 00:06:40.220
That could be with some new technology.

00:06:40.220 --> 00:06:44.500
That's our lean on it.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:48.579
Beyond that, get paid slash reduce cost.

00:06:48.579 --> 00:06:51.100
And then lastly, refine and repeat.

00:06:51.100 --> 00:07:01.660
So that's kind of how we stay practical, I guess, with all of our solutions.

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:08.980
One example prototype, you know, walking through or framing it in that same way.

00:07:08.980 --> 00:07:13.859
So one issue if you've built shiny applications is that they will freeze when running a long

00:07:13.859 --> 00:07:16.700
running job.

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:22.019
And the application will just stop working.

00:07:22.019 --> 00:07:31.100
And so the solution to that is to use� or to enable asynchronous processing.

00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:34.980
There's a variety of ways to do that.

00:07:34.980 --> 00:07:40.700
So at Lilly, there's a great developer, Will Landau, he's made a number of tools.

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:50.459
One is crew, which helps to facilitate spinning up independent workers and running a job from

00:07:50.459 --> 00:07:53.579
an existing R session.

00:07:53.579 --> 00:07:57.660
And so we put together a basic prototype to see, could this solve our problem?

00:07:57.660 --> 00:08:02.339
And if so, you know, what does that look like?

00:08:02.339 --> 00:08:08.980
So we built it on our� in this case, we didn't necessarily get paid.

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:15.660
It does drive impact by making the applications more usable and broadening our impact.

00:08:15.660 --> 00:08:22.859
And then lastly, on the step for refining and repeating, it was open sourced and people

00:08:22.859 --> 00:08:25.619
continued to build on it.

00:08:25.619 --> 00:08:34.260
And the direction our team has gone has been to enable offloading those independent workers

00:08:34.260 --> 00:08:35.780
into new compute environments.

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:42.619
So that's how we iterate.

00:08:42.619 --> 00:08:49.020
And so on the topic of what is a prototype, it's important to define what your finish

00:08:49.020 --> 00:08:50.299
line is.

00:08:50.299 --> 00:08:54.460
Because you don't just want to blindly be going out and building a prototype and without

00:08:54.460 --> 00:09:00.940
much direction or aim, kind of just continuing to iterate.

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:05.580
And so for us, the finish line is typically, you know, either it's a pre-specified set

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:14.739
of features, oftentimes it's a guidance on go or no-go for future development.

00:09:14.739 --> 00:09:22.219
Or in that same vein, providing the guidance on, okay, if you want to mature the software,

00:09:22.219 --> 00:09:26.580
what would that take to move it to the next stage?

00:09:26.580 --> 00:09:28.900
Yeah.

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:29.900
And moving on.

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:38.659
So this is a scorecard that we've put together as a team to define what those other stages

00:09:38.659 --> 00:09:40.619
look like.

00:09:40.619 --> 00:09:47.299
And so in the leftmost column, you have the software maturity stage.

00:09:47.299 --> 00:09:52.700
So we end up spending most of our time in the POC or functional prototype.

00:09:52.700 --> 00:09:58.260
But then you can move on to, you know, alpha or beta releases, where you're broadening

00:09:58.260 --> 00:10:05.820
out that end user group or eventually taking it on to production software, where people

00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:10.219
are using it to make important decisions.

00:10:10.219 --> 00:10:17.059
And so going from that leftmost column, moving over, we have things like having end user

00:10:17.059 --> 00:10:23.739
testing, you know, the documentation, more unit testing, integration testing, and working

00:10:23.739 --> 00:10:25.700
with IT as well.

00:10:25.700 --> 00:10:33.900
But, yeah, like I said, we spend most of our time in the POC to alpha or beta release.

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:40.200
And then when it comes to moving things on to production, usually we'll simply provide

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:45.059
the guidance and start working with the teams for a handoff or something like that.

00:10:46.059 --> 00:10:48.820
All right.

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:55.460
And so moving on to how we operate as a team.

00:10:55.460 --> 00:11:00.239
So again, it's just me, James, the other guy.

00:11:00.239 --> 00:11:02.840
We check in daily.

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:04.260
We don't have a project manager.

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:08.219
We project manage ourselves.

00:11:08.940 --> 00:11:15.419
Typically, we're working on two to three prototypes at a time.

00:11:15.419 --> 00:11:20.219
And they take anywhere from a few weeks to a few months to complete.

00:11:20.219 --> 00:11:28.260
As far as setting goals as a team, we use the objectives and key results framework.

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:32.859
And so every quarter, we kind of set some big picture goals.

00:11:32.859 --> 00:11:40.859
For example, one is to complete ten prototypes in the next quarter as a team.

00:11:40.859 --> 00:11:47.859
And that allows us it's a good mix of kind of long and short term goals.

00:11:47.859 --> 00:11:50.299
So we have three months to work on those prototypes.

00:11:50.299 --> 00:11:56.500
But then we have a lot of flexibility in between and defining what those prototypes are, what

00:11:56.500 --> 00:11:59.219
teams or groups we're working with.

00:12:00.179 --> 00:12:03.580
Yeah, another thing we do is we make our goals widely available.

00:12:03.580 --> 00:12:09.859
And at those quarterly check-ins, we meet with a lot of the sponsors for the team

00:12:09.859 --> 00:12:13.419
or the stakeholders and reset the goals.

00:12:13.419 --> 00:12:21.739
We make our goals widely available so anyone can look at them, provide input to them.

00:12:21.739 --> 00:12:27.419
Yeah, and then lastly, this is a fun one, or at least I think it's a fun one.

00:12:27.419 --> 00:12:31.739
We also do a retrospective, and we do something called a fear setting exercise.

00:12:31.739 --> 00:12:37.940
I saw it in a TED Talk and tried it out, and we've done a few now.

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:39.460
And we did this fear setting.

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:46.539
So if you haven't seen it or heard about it, it's kind of the opposite of goal setting,

00:12:46.539 --> 00:12:52.739
which I think scared my manager when I first pitched it.

00:12:52.739 --> 00:12:56.739
So fear setting, it's useful for someone like me.

00:12:56.739 --> 00:13:01.140
So I'm very optimistic, but I also like taking risks.

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:08.859
And so that can be trouble because those anxieties or that voice in your head saying, no, don't

00:13:08.859 --> 00:13:12.299
do it, can be useful.

00:13:12.299 --> 00:13:16.200
And so the fear setting kind of facilitates that.

00:13:16.200 --> 00:13:26.419
So what we'll do is we'll talk about ways that our group, like something could go wrong

00:13:27.099 --> 00:13:34.099
or one example would be like we start working with a certain team, and they want to use

00:13:34.099 --> 00:13:36.900
all of our resources, and so we can't really work on the other stuff.

00:13:36.900 --> 00:13:38.580
So that's a big fear.

00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:43.419
We don't just want to be a shop for one team.

00:13:43.419 --> 00:13:50.020
And so going beyond that fear, it's not just like we talk about them, and then we get paralyzed

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:51.020
by them.

00:13:51.020 --> 00:13:53.780
Then we talk about, OK, what if that did happen?

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:56.299
What do we do?

00:13:57.179 --> 00:14:03.219
What can we introduce maybe to our goals to make sure that that kind of thing isn't happening?

00:14:03.219 --> 00:14:11.500
So yeah, and another fun part of that is, like I said, I lean towards more like being

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:21.380
optimistic, and there's definitely some, I don't know, there's people that are on the

00:14:21.380 --> 00:14:29.219
other side of that spectrum, more cautious, more anxious, a lot of fears, and it's fun

00:14:29.219 --> 00:14:35.299
to recruit them because I rely on that because I'm like, I don't, you know, honestly, I don't

00:14:35.299 --> 00:14:36.780
even know what, I have a blind spot.

00:14:36.780 --> 00:14:39.739
I don't know what my fears should be.

00:14:39.739 --> 00:14:43.739
And so yeah, relying on them is really valuable.

00:14:43.739 --> 00:14:50.020
And I, yeah, yeah, the guy I'm thinking about, I was skeptical, I was like, I don't even

00:14:50.020 --> 00:14:53.340
know if he's going to want to join this, but he had a blast and keeps showing up to

00:14:53.340 --> 00:14:54.340
him.

00:14:54.340 --> 00:14:59.299
So yeah, all righty.

00:14:59.299 --> 00:15:04.659
And lastly, just to share some of the lessons learned.

00:15:04.659 --> 00:15:10.780
Like I mentioned earlier, conversation around innovation will be elevated.

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:16.580
I think it's in the spirit of organizations transitioning from waterfall to agile, but

00:15:16.580 --> 00:15:26.380
instead of taking gigantic, you know, multi-year projects that have a lot of risk, and yeah,

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:33.940
you can balance that with doing smaller projects, testing the waters, learning more about it,

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:43.140
and yeah, lifting up the entire conversation, both on the development side and within leadership.

00:15:43.659 --> 00:15:51.580
So you will fail often, but more than make up for it with reducing cost and accelerating

00:15:51.580 --> 00:15:52.580
learning.

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:58.539
Yeah, I think as a team, this is going to sound strange, but I wish we failed more.

00:15:58.539 --> 00:16:04.020
And I think my manager has said we should fail more.

00:16:04.020 --> 00:16:10.119
And we do fail, but I think when you're failing more, you're taking, you know, you're pushing

00:16:10.119 --> 00:16:11.900
the boundaries more.

00:16:11.940 --> 00:16:15.299
And so that's an important part of it.

00:16:15.299 --> 00:16:21.700
And beyond failing, you know, obviously, you're learning from those prototypes.

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:26.260
As I mentioned earlier, it's a very small team.

00:16:26.260 --> 00:16:31.820
I really think you can do a lot with a small, scrappy team, especially in that earlier phase

00:16:31.820 --> 00:16:34.099
for software maturity.

00:16:34.099 --> 00:16:39.419
When you're talking about production software, there's more important things than moving

00:16:39.419 --> 00:16:41.140
fast necessarily.

00:16:41.140 --> 00:16:45.140
You want reliability and quality with a lot of that stuff.

00:16:45.140 --> 00:16:49.960
It's harder to move faster with a big team.

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:54.380
And also with older, more mature software, it's harder to make the updates.

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:59.940
So that's where having, yeah, prototypes is really valuable.

00:16:59.940 --> 00:17:05.280
Next, I'd say iteration is not just for software.

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:07.560
It's really good for metrics as well.

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:16.079
So earlier I mentioned one of our metrics or goals is to complete 10 prototypes a quarter.

00:17:16.079 --> 00:17:21.239
And some of you may have listened to that and said, well, that's not a really good metric.

00:17:21.239 --> 00:17:23.239
And it's one we work on too.

00:17:23.239 --> 00:17:30.180
So there's certainly different flavors of what that metric could be.

00:17:30.180 --> 00:17:31.839
Right now it's a good volume.

00:17:31.839 --> 00:17:33.160
We're adjusting it.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:40.239
But, yeah, one thing that has come out of this is that those metrics need to be updated.

00:17:40.239 --> 00:17:42.479
We revisit them on a quarterly basis.

00:17:42.479 --> 00:17:48.920
But, yeah, it's good to have that flexibility to iterate on metrics as well.

00:17:48.920 --> 00:17:54.640
Next, spending some time with your fears is incredibly valuable.

00:17:54.640 --> 00:18:00.520
Yeah, I think, you know, I shared earlier how it's good for people that lean towards

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:03.040
being more optimistic.

00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:08.280
But I think it's also good for people that spend more time with their anxieties because

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:15.119
it kind of forces people to go, you know, from those fears to, like, okay, let's say

00:18:15.119 --> 00:18:16.280
it does happen.

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:17.920
Then what?

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:23.560
And you're not just stuck in that, you know, cycle of thinking about what could potentially

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:27.599
go wrong.

00:18:27.599 --> 00:18:30.599
Experimenting early and often is a huge accelerator.

00:18:31.160 --> 00:18:34.880
Yeah, can't emphasize that enough.

00:18:34.880 --> 00:18:40.160
And then lastly, I would say statisticians are becoming software developers.

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:44.160
That's a big narrative within our organization.

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:51.439
And having the prototypes team exist to bridge that gap is very valuable.

00:18:51.439 --> 00:18:58.640
I think we're key to testing and vetting the new ideas, new technologies, new processes

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:03.880
that the rest of the organization is starting to test the waters with.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:06.560
And we get to be the guinea pigs to share those learnings out.

00:19:06.560 --> 00:19:07.560
So yeah.

00:19:07.560 --> 00:19:08.560
All right.

00:19:08.560 --> 00:19:10.319
Well, that is all I have.

00:19:10.319 --> 00:19:19.479
So thank you, everyone, for coming to the talk today.

00:19:19.479 --> 00:19:20.479
Thank you, Daniel.

00:19:20.479 --> 00:19:21.479
Yeah.

00:19:21.479 --> 00:19:24.479
We will have time for a single question.

00:19:24.479 --> 00:19:29.239
And so it must be really tempting to keep working the prototype to production.

00:19:29.239 --> 00:19:34.479
How do you decide when enough is enough?

00:19:34.479 --> 00:19:36.300
That is a great question.

00:19:36.300 --> 00:19:40.479
We haven't been forced that yet.

00:19:40.479 --> 00:19:42.800
Yeah.

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:46.479
When to decide when to move, like, a prototype to production.

00:19:46.479 --> 00:19:48.500
So a lot of it ends up coming.

00:19:48.500 --> 00:19:53.000
So we'll provide, like I said, a go or no-go decision, and then we'll do some evaluation

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.280
on, like, okay, you want to take it to the next phase?

00:19:57.280 --> 00:19:58.800
Here's what that would take.

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:08.239
And our team really isn't set up for supporting the QA process with IT, monitoring infrastructure,

00:20:08.239 --> 00:20:09.239
things like that.

00:20:09.239 --> 00:20:10.239
So yeah.

00:20:10.239 --> 00:20:17.359
I think having that conversation early and up front is important.

00:20:17.359 --> 00:20:22.079
Because that's definitely the direction it would go is and we don't want to be a team

00:20:22.160 --> 00:20:25.640
that is just supporting the production software.

00:20:25.640 --> 00:20:28.599
It stops us from accelerating those conversations.

00:20:28.599 --> 00:20:29.599
So.

00:20:29.599 --> 00:20:30.599
Fantastic.

00:20:30.599 --> 00:20:31.599
Thank you again, Daniel.

00:20:31.599 --> 00:20:32.599
Yep.

